		<SceneContent><![CDATA[Lowell sank to the ground as he watched Charlie ride off with Roxie. His feet just wouldn't take him any farther. He didn't know what had upset Charlie so much, but he hated when she was angry with him.

Once he collected himself, he rose to his feet again and stormed back into the almost empty bar. Jess still sat on her stool at the bar. She usually hung around in the early afternoon hours, since she wasn't working yet. Rachel was cleaning tables and loading dishes into the buspans. Junie had been watching him from the window and was backing away when he came in. All eyes were on him. He glowered at Junie.

"Junie, please stop harrassing me. I have told you repeatedly that nothing is going to happen, and I'm not going to change my mind." He really tried to stay calm, but he was afraid his voice sounded more like a growl.

"But, I --"

"Junie," still growling, and still trying to keep his cool. "Nothing is going to happen. I am not into you. What you've been doing is embarrasing for you, and harrassing me."

"Then why have you kept me around so long? If it's really that much of a bother --"

Lowell closed his eyes and took a deep breath as her voice faded away. "You know, Junie. I felt sorry for you. You are good to the customers, you've been here a long time, and I needed the help. But I can always find other help." His words clipped short as he continued. "Should I do that, or can you control yourself?"

She was shaking and Lowell felt a little guilty. He knew his quiet anger was intimidating to most people, but it was all he could muster at this point. Jess rose from her stool and came to Junie's side, eyes still on Lowell.

Junie's voice quivered. "Lowell, I -- I really thought you liked having me around. But if you don't want me here, I can leave."

"Can you control yourself, Junie?"

"Uh, yes, I think so."

"Good. Then you have one last chance to be my employee, and nothing more. We aren't even friends, Junie. Do you understand that?"

Tears streamed down her face as she answered. "Yes, Lowell. We aren't even friends. Thank you."

Lowell looked at Rachel as Junie sank into a chair. "Rachel, you are my witness, and you are in charge here in the front of the house. If there is anymore harrassment, you may fire her. I'm tired of avoiding people in my own place. Got it?" Rachel nodded. "Good. I'm going out, and I'll be back before the dinner rush."

He took two steps, then stopped. Looking at the women, he hesitated. "I really want to yell right now, but I don't think there's anything else to say."

"No, boss," Rachel said. "I think you've said plenty."

He headed upstairs and overheard Jess and Rachel consoling Junie.

"What did you think was gonna happen, Junie? That he was gonna suddenly decide to screw you, and that'd be it?" Rachel snapped.

"Rachel, that isn't very nice. He really hurt her feelings," Jess said, trying to be neutral.

"Jess, she's been pulling the same act for as long as I've known her. I can't believe he put up with it as long as he did. I mean, if no means no when we say it, why shouldn't it for him? Why does he have to be the bad guy?"

"But, I love him, Rachel," Junie squeaked. "I have wanted him since high school, and I just don't know how to quit."

"Oh Junie, you don't need that kind of love. You need someone who can love you back. It doesn't seem like Lowell does," said Jess. "Take it from someone who knows. You deserve to have someone who loves you back." Jess reached out to Junie and hugged her.

Junie sobbed. "What am I gonna do?"

Rachel rolled her eyes and scoffed as she turned back to her work. Jess patted Junie's back and said, "You're going to pick yourself up, be the best employee ever, and start making new friends that aren't Lowell."]]></SceneContent>
