		<SceneContent><![CDATA[The wind cooled Charlie's face. Riding was so freeing, and she could always think clearly on the back of a motorcycle. So what if Lowell was with someone else. So what if he had a girlfriend. It explained why he stopped her last night, but it didn't explain this morning. What they had was casual, but she would be damned if she was going to be the other woman.

Well, that doesn't make sense either. If what they have is casual, then there will be others. She will be the other woman. It's not up to her to decide that he has something special with someone else. Right? Gah - this was all so confusing.

The bike slowed and Roxie pulled over to the side of the road.

"You've got to tell me where to steer this thing. I don't know where you want to go," he said.

"Can't we just keep riding?" she asked hopefully.

Roxie turned around in his seat. "Hon, I'd love to, but you keep muttering to yourself back there, and I'm afraid you're gonna jump off. You are not alright, and I want to talk with you. Should we do it here, or do you want to go somewhere?"

"The cemetery. I'll drive" she said, firmly. She needed to talk to Chase.

She climbed off the bike so Roxie could get off without kicking her. Then, she got back on, and he followed. She started up the bike and turned around to head back towards town. The cemetery was on the edge of town, so she wouldn't risk running into Lowell, or anyone else she knew.

She pulled into the driveway of the cemetery and parked the bike near the section where Chase was buried. They got off the bike and walked the the site.

"So, this is it, huh?" Roxie said, looking at the headstone.

"This is it," confirmed Charlie, moving to the large tree near the gravesite. She sank down to the ground and leaned against the tree.

Roxie crouched down and fingered the key chains. "You come here a lot, I guess."

"Yeah, every year. I get little trinkets for him while I'm gone, and I leave them when I come back."

Roxie rose to his feet and joined her under the tree. He took her hand and laced his fingers with hers. "Chuckie, I don't know what to say. You know this isn't healthy, right? Running around like you don't have a home, or people who miss you."

"I am tired of being on the road all the time, but I like having connections with people that didn't know Chase. I can feel everyone's eyes on me here. Like they're waiting for me to do something or be somebody. But I don't know who I am without him when I'm here. Out there, it's easier."

"Yeah, I get that. But you have to find balance. You have to deal with this grief. And you have to let your family grieve with you, too. They lost your brother, too, you know."

"Yeah, I know. I'm getting that. But I don't know how to fill the void he left."

"You mean, like, in your family?"

"Yeah. The role he played in the house and with my parents. I can't fill that."

"Honey, what ever made you think you had to?"

"Well, I guess I -- I don't know. I guess I thought because we were twins that I had to somehow make up for him being gone."

Roxie smiled. "No offense, doll, but that's just dumb. You can't make up for a whole person being gone. You have to just be you. Your family will find a way to get along without him. But to lose you, too? I don't know many families that could handle that."

Charlie understood what he was saying, but she didn't really see it. Her parents and Kenny seemed to be getting along just fine without her. Roxie continued, "But the big difference I see is that Chase was lost through fate. You chose to be lost."

Just then an old truck rolled up, and Lowell parked next to the bike. Roxie kissed the back of her hand and stood up, letting her hand drop to her lap.

"Looks like my turn is over. Text me if you need me; I won't be far." Charlie nodded and he walked away, nodding at Lowell as they passed each other.]]></SceneContent>
